postcontent:
Selling my used AK74 style brake from Tapco. I fired 200 rounds through my AK with this on with noticeable reduction in recoil and muzzle flip. Comfort was our biggest motivation in the design of our unique holsters. Each Series of Nate Squared Tactical holsters are made from quality oil-tanned leather, neoprene, and suede leather. title: For Sale:  Saiga AK Tactical SHTF MBR 5.56 NATO
postcontent:
This is the ultimate rifle for any SHTF scenario. With reduced weight due to polymer and aluminum furniture and ample rail space for optics and attachments, as well as the reliability of the AK design chambered in a common (and cheap) U.S. round, this should probably be the one rifle you own.

This is a Russian Saiga AK factory chambered in 5.56x45 with bullet guide installed to accept Galil mags. Saigas are the only new Russian AKs on the civilian market. It has been converted to the standard AK pistol grip (Polymer) configuration with polymer Warsaw length buttstock. One 30 round polymer Galil mag comes with the rifle.

A chaos rail system has been installed with a dogleg rail over the dust cover and a quad rail on the forearm. Rails are made of aluminum with a black powder coating. The FSB has been removed, with MBUS flip sights on the rails added for sighting. Glass can be added at the dust cover or forearm. The barrel has been threaded for 15x1M (HK) muzzle adapters and re-crowned with a .223 target crown. The bore is in excellent condition with less than 250 rounds through it. It comes with an AK-74 type compensator, vertical grip, and recoil buffer. The conversion was done with Tapco trigger parts from Carolina Shooter Supply as part of their 5.56 Saiga conversion package. A textured tromix bolt handle has been added for easier hand cycling, and a Kreb's peep sight is attached for use with an added front sight like a gas block sight.

I have a lot in this rifle ($1,200+), and it is an amazing shooter with a crisp trigger pull and a smooth action. It could use a bit of touch up as far as the finish is concerned, but other than that, it is solid. Willing to work with anyone on the price.

$800 OBO. I am open to a trade, and am looking for a Ruger Gunsite Scout or comparable scout rifle.

title: For Sale:  win-13
postcontent:
Winchester WIN-13 in very good condition. Serial number puts this rifle in the first batch of WIN-13s produced. All parts are marked WRA for Winchester Repeating Arms except for the 1948 Springfield Armory barrel which was probably installed by the CMP. Muzzle wear is about a 1.5.  Original parkerized finish is a nice uniform patina. Stock and handguards are in good shape with typical dings and dents but no repairs or cracks that I can see. This rifle will ship in original CMP hardcase with all the paper work that came with it from CMP.

A short history of the WIN-13 Garand by Major Dick Culver:

"Winchester was producing rifles in the 2,5XX,XXX number range in early January 1945 and suddenly and inexplicably started producing rifles with a lower serial number range starting with 1,601,000. This series of serial numbers continued through Winchester's final production at serial number 1,640,000 in June 1945 for a total of 39,000 rifles. Starting with serial number1.601,000, Winchester changed their drawing number on the right leg of the receiver from D28291-2 to D28291-Win-13. 

Production total of 39,000 rifles places the Win-13s in a position of relative rarity and the Win-13 has become one of the more sought after variations of the M1 rifle. An air of mystery will always surround the serial number switch that caused this interesting Winchester variation to be one of the least common W.W.II production rifles."

title: For Sale:  Lee-Enfield No. 4 Mk I
postcontent:
Rifle No. 4
Lee-Enfield No. 4 Mk I

By the late 1930s the need for new rifles grew and the Rifle, No. 4 Mk I was first issued in 1939 but not officially adopted until 1941. The No. 4 action was similar to the Mk VI, but lighter, stronger, and most importantly, easier to mass-produce. Unlike the SMLE, the No 4 Lee-Enfield barrel protruded from the end of the forestock. The No. 4 rifle was considerably heavier than the No. 1 Mk. III, largely due to its heavier barrel and a new bayonet was designed to go with the rifle: a spike bayonet, which was essentially a steel rod with a sharp point and was nicknamed "pigsticker" by soldiers. Towards the end of the Second World War, a bladed bayonet was developed, originally intended for use with the Sten gun‚Äîbut sharing the same mount as the No. 4's spike bayonet‚Äîand subsequently the No. 7 and No. 9 blade bayonets were issued for use with the No. 4 rifle as well.
